  "prompt": "Can I get into grad school with 2 C's?",
  "response": "Whether you can get into graduate school with two C's on your transcript depends on several factors:\n\n1. **Field of Study**: Some fields may be more forgiving of lower grades than others. For example, certain humanities programs might weigh overall experience and potential more heavily, whereas STEM programs often look for strong academic performance.\n\n2. **Overall GPA**: If your overall GPA is strong, two C's may not significantly impact your application. Many graduate programs look at the cumulative GPA and may consider the context of those grades.\n\n3. **Prerequisites**: If the C's are in prerequisite courses for the program you\u2019re applying to, it might raise concerns about your preparedness for graduate-level work.\n\n4. **Trends in Performance**: If you demonstrate an upward trend in your grades, especially in relevant courses, this can help offset the lower grades. Admissions committees often look for improvement and a strong finish.\n\n5. **Letters of Recommendation**: Strong letters from professors or professionals in your field can enhance your application, especially if they can speak to your skills and potential despite the C's.\n\n6. **Statement of Purpose**: You can address any challenges you faced and explain how you\u2019ve grown since then, emphasizing your passion for the field and your readiness for graduate study.\n\n7. **Test Scores**: If applicable, strong GRE or other standardized test scores can help bolster your application.\n\n8. **Experience**: Relevant work, research, or volunteer experience can also strengthen your application and demonstrate your commitment and capabilities.\n\nUltimately, each program and its admissions committee will weigh these factors differently. If you're concerned, consider reaching out to prospective programs to gauge how they view grades in the context of your overall application.",
